	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>WTO: New Zealand backs Pacific islands to exempt fisheries fees </h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 March 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> According to <i>Islands Business</i>, New Zealand may agree to back the calls from developing countries to exempt fishery access fees from the definition of subsidies. The ‘Friends of Fish’ group, of which New Zealand is a member, had initially opposed such calls. But following submissions from countries in the Pacific, which derive up to US$70 million annually from fishing licenses and access fees, New Zealand begun to recognise that some components of access fees are developmental assistance and therefore could be exempted.</p><p> Through the assistance of the Commonwealth Secretariat in London, Fiji was able to approach the New Zealand delegation at last December’s WTO conference in Hong Kong ‘to agree to a joint declaration that will specifically spell out the support for fisheries subsidies for developmental purposes for small-island states, in particular, because of the peculiarity of our geography and maritime nature’.</p><p>
 The Pacific Islands Forum has taken the lead in ensuring that the Pacific Islands countries’ concerns and plights are heard loud and clear in the WTO discussions. It is felt that negotiations on the subject ought to focus on the trade effects of fishing subsidies and not on other issues like over-capacity and over-fishing.<br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Islands Business</i>, March 2006</p><p>

<a href="http://www.islandsbusiness.com/islands_business/index_dynamic/containerNameToReplace=MiddleMiddle/focusModuleID=5628/overideSkinName=issueArticle-full.tpl" target="_self">http://www.islandsbusiness.com/islands_business/index_dynamic/containerN...</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The issue of access fees in the fishery-subsidy negotiations is of prime concern to many ACP coastal states, particularly those that have fishery agreements with the EU. The EU considers that access fees that it pays cannot be considered as a subsidy. Rather it is a contribution justified by mutual interest, to provide adequate support to the development and the management of a sustainable fishing policy in the third countries where the European fleet is operating. However, such a claim has yet to be recognised in the WTO negotiations.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
